====Usage notes====
A, in the distributive sense "ten hours a day," has traditionally been considered preferable to ''per,'' which originated in [[commercialese]] and legalese. But ''per'' has muscled its way into idiomatic English in phrases such as "60 miles per hour," "one golf cart per couple," and "five books per student." Although ''an'' could be substituted for ''per'' in the first of those phrases, ''a'' wouldn't work well in the second or third.

When the construction requires a phrasal adjective, ''per'' is the only idiomatic wordβÄîe.g., βÄ€Our per-unit cost is less than $1,000.βÄù/ βÄ€The $50-per-parent fee seems unreasonably high.βÄù

